Oh, he's not very
well, I'm afraid.

805
00:38:34,211 --> 00:38:35,112
Please sit.

806
00:38:37,848 --> 00:38:41,285
I want Shannon to
be buried in this.

807
00:38:41,385 --> 00:38:43,054
Of course.

808
00:38:43,154 --> 00:38:45,756
Is there anything else I can do?

809
00:38:45,856 --> 00:38:47,458
Yes.

810
00:38:47,558 --> 00:38:49,627
When they bring the
body in, I'd like you

811
00:38:49,727 --> 00:38:51,729
to look under her fingernails.

812
00:38:51,829 --> 00:38:54,665
See if there's any evidence
of Shannon's having

813
00:38:54,765 --> 00:38:56,934
clawed or scratched somebody.

814
00:38:57,034 --> 00:38:57,835
I'm sorry, Cille.

815
00:38:57,935 --> 00:38:59,403
It's too late for that.

816
00:38:59,503 --> 00:39:00,771
Why too late?

817
00:39:00,871 --> 00:39:03,874
The body's already here,
been embalmed, and cleaned.

818
00:39:06,444 --> 00:39:09,313
Well, how could they have
finished the autopsy so soon?

819
00:39:09,413 --> 00:39:10,414
There was no autopsy.

820
00:39:10,514 --> 00:39:13,417
[music playing]

821
00:39:22,393 --> 00:39:25,096
Shannon Moore Davis lived
her life with a sweetness that

822
00:39:25,196 --> 00:39:28,566
left its mark on everyone here.

823
00:39:28,666 --> 00:39:31,302
As we commend her
body to the ground,

824
00:39:31,402 --> 00:39:37,441
realize her spirit dwells
in each and every one of us.

825
00:39:37,541 --> 00:39:39,410
May the Lord welcome
Shannon on her journey

826
00:39:39,510 --> 00:39:44,248
to the table of Gods
children in heaven with faith

827
00:39:44,348 --> 00:39:47,218
and hope in eternal peace.

828
00:39:47,318 --> 00:39:50,721
Let us assist her now
with a silent prayer.

829
00:39:50,821 --> 00:39:54,291
[gentle music]

830
00:40:03,300 --> 00:40:04,168
Aunt Cille.

831
00:40:04,268 --> 00:40:05,169
Hi, Teresa.

832
00:40:09,840 --> 00:40:10,741
Dave.

833
00:40:13,477 --> 00:40:15,379
Dave, we're just so sorry.

834
00:40:15,479 --> 00:40:17,748
I really appreciate
having friends like you.

835
00:40:17,848 --> 00:40:19,884
Shannon and I were very lucky.

836
00:40:19,984 --> 00:40:21,419
Excuse me.

837
00:40:21,519 --> 00:40:23,821
Mrs. Warrick, I'm sorry.

838
00:40:26,557 --> 00:40:28,692
I'm-- I'm curious.

839
00:40:28,793 --> 00:40:30,327
Do you know when the
death certificate

840
00:40:30,428 --> 00:40:32,530
will become available?

841
00:40:32,630 --> 00:40:34,598
Well, that usually happens
within a couple of weeks.

842
00:40:34,698 --> 00:40:35,533
It's a paperwork thing.

843
00:40:35,633 --> 00:40:36,434
But it won't be long.

844
00:40:36,534 --> 00:40:37,568
Would you do me a favor?

845
00:40:37,668 --> 00:40:39,370
Would you please let me
know when you have it?

846
00:40:39,470 --> 00:40:40,938
I'd like to have a copy.

847
00:40:41,038 --> 00:40:42,072
Of course.

848
00:40:42,173 --> 00:40:43,073
Thank you.

849
00:40:45,843 --> 00:40:46,644
Thank you, Mark.

850
00:40:46,744 --> 00:40:48,546
Thank you very much.

851
00:40:48,646 --> 00:40:49,447
Mr. Moore.

852
00:40:49,547 --> 00:40:50,514
Yes.

853
00:40:50,614 --> 00:40:52,817
I'm Jane Thomas,
Dave's mother.

854
00:40:52,917 --> 00:40:54,318
Oh, please.
Sit down.

855
00:40:54,418 --> 00:40:55,219
Thank you.

856
00:40:55,319 --> 00:40:56,854
It's so nice to meet you.

857
00:40:56,954 --> 00:40:59,990
Not under these
circumstances I'm sure.

858
00:41:00,057 --> 00:41:02,026
I'm so sorry.

859
00:41:02,126 --> 00:41:05,463
They've told me what a
wonderful girl Shannon was.

860
00:41:05,563 --> 00:41:06,697
Thank you.

861
00:41:06,797 --> 00:41:08,532
I don't want to
disturb your wife,

862
00:41:08,632 --> 00:41:11,135
but please tell
her how sorry I am.

863
00:41:11,235 --> 00:41:14,004
And-- and sorry that they
never had a wedding where

864
00:41:14,104 --> 00:41:16,006
we all could have met earlier.

865
00:41:19,043 --> 00:41:20,211
Dave worshipped Shannon.

866
00:41:20,311 --> 00:41:22,446
I just don't know how
he's going to handle this.

867
00:41:22,546 --> 00:41:23,614
Yes.

868
00:41:23,714 --> 00:41:27,351
After all the other
things he's been through.

869
00:41:27,451 --> 00:41:28,686
How's that?

870
00:41:28,786 --> 00:41:30,921
Well, you know, the
Vietnam and friends

871
00:41:31,021 --> 00:41:33,457
of his dying in his arms.

872
00:41:33,557 --> 00:41:35,259
Vietnam?

873
00:41:35,359 --> 00:41:36,393
There must be some mistake.

874
00:41:38,996 --> 00:41:40,664
What do you mean?

875
00:41:40,764 --> 00:41:43,300
He was never in Vietnam.

876
00:41:43,400 --> 00:41:44,802
The Marines?

877
00:41:44,902 --> 00:41:46,136
No, not the Marines either.

878
00:41:50,574 --> 00:41:53,644
Just after the
funeral, a group of us

879
00:41:53,744 --> 00:41:57,882
went to dinner to get
our minds off of it.

880
00:41:57,982 --> 00:42:00,684
Dave ordered
Margaritas and nachos.

881
00:42:00,784 --> 00:42:04,488
And when the drinks came,
he made a toast to Shannon.

882
00:42:07,491 --> 00:42:08,559
It was really bad.

883
00:42:08,659 --> 00:42:13,964
It went-- it went
something like to my loving

884
00:42:14,064 --> 00:42:21,171
wife, who is now smiling down on
us, I wouldn't change a thing.

885
00:42:21,272 --> 00:42:22,840
I just wish that she
could have cooked better.

886
00:42:22,940 --> 00:42:25,676
[music playing]

887
00:42:36,487 --> 00:42:38,689
Hey, babe, it's me.

888
00:42:38,789 --> 00:42:40,591
Papers are saying
that girl's dead, Dave.

889
00:42:40,691 --> 00:42:42,159
What's going on?

890
00:42:42,259 --> 00:42:45,195
She's as alive as you and me.

891
00:42:45,296 --> 00:42:47,064
Dave, she fell off
a horse and died.

892
00:42:47,164 --> 00:42:48,699
It's here in black and white.

893
00:42:48,799 --> 00:42:50,467
You ought to know better
than to believe everything

894
00:42:50,568 --> 00:42:51,535
you read in the papers.

895
00:42:51,635 --> 00:42:53,270
What are you telling me, Dave?

896
00:42:53,370 --> 00:42:55,072
What are you telling me?

897
00:42:55,172 --> 00:42:58,208
This woman has a
new name, a new house,

898
00:42:58,309 --> 00:43:01,512
someone new to watch over her.

899
00:43:01,612 --> 00:43:03,847
So your job is over now?

900
00:43:03,948 --> 00:43:06,917
I'm packing for a little
R&R in the Florida sun.

901
00:43:07,017 --> 00:43:07,952
I want to come with you.

902
00:43:08,052 --> 00:43:08,852
Why not?

903
00:43:08,953 --> 00:43:11,789
[intense music]

904
00:43:13,657 --> 00:43:15,826
Cille, I just got off the
phone with the funeral parlor.

905
00:43:15,926 --> 00:43:17,394
Dave's just coming
up the sidewalk.

906
00:43:17,494 --> 00:43:18,362
Listen to me, Cille.

907
00:43:18,462 --> 00:43:19,964
The lady at the
funeral parlor said

908
00:43:20,064 --> 00:43:21,999
that six separate
insurance companies called.

909
00:43:22,099 --> 00:43:23,767
They want to see copies
of the death certificates.

910
00:43:23,867 --> 00:43:24,969
What do we say to him now?

911
00:43:25,069 --> 00:43:26,003
Nothing.

912
00:43:26,103 --> 00:43:27,204
We don't want him to
know that we know.

913
00:43:27,304 --> 00:43:28,105
All right.

914
00:43:28,205 --> 00:43:31,275
[knocking]

915
00:43:41,752 --> 00:43:43,854
What's wrong?

916
00:43:43,954 --> 00:43:46,790
I've had a bad day.

917
00:43:46,890 --> 00:43:48,692
I'm sure you
understand that, Dave?

918
00:43:51,261 --> 00:43:54,932
These are some things I'm sure
Shannon would want you to have.

919
00:43:55,032 --> 00:43:56,400
You can come out to the
house later and look

920
00:43:56,500 --> 00:43:57,801
around after I get back.

921
00:43:57,901 --> 00:44:00,104
Oh, you're going someplace?

922
00:44:00,204 --> 00:44:02,006
I just got to get out of here.

923
00:44:02,106 --> 00:44:03,140
I'm sure you do.

924
00:44:06,143 --> 00:44:08,078
I'll be in the desert.

925
00:44:08,178 --> 00:44:09,380
Don't know where.

926
00:44:09,480 --> 00:44:14,051
I'm just going to keep
driving, trying to heal.

927
00:44:20,424 --> 00:44:21,925
Well, I guess that's it.

928
00:44:22,026 --> 00:44:25,496
Dave, how do we reach
you if we want to--

929
00:44:25,596 --> 00:44:26,830
Well, you can't.

930
00:44:26,930 --> 00:44:29,767
There are no phones
in the desert.

931
00:44:29,867 --> 00:44:33,370
[music playing]

932
00:44:46,150 --> 00:44:46,950
Jerri!

933
00:44:47,051 --> 00:44:47,851
Jerri!

934
00:44:47,951 --> 00:44:49,987
[music playing]

935
00:44:53,791 --> 00:44:54,792
Did you get your errand done?

936
00:44:54,892 --> 00:44:55,693
Oh, fine.

937
00:44:55,793 --> 00:44:56,593
No problem.

938
00:44:56,694 --> 00:44:57,761
Great.

939
00:44:57,861 --> 00:44:58,762
Oh.

940
00:45:02,132 --> 00:45:03,267
I can't wait to get to Florida.

941
00:45:03,367 --> 00:45:04,168
Me neither.

942
00:45:04,268 --> 00:45:06,970
[music playing]

943
00:45:08,806 --> 00:45:10,841
Well, I'd really like
to help you, Mrs. Moore.

944
00:45:10,941 --> 00:45:14,445
But there are no laws against
travel in this country.

945
00:45:14,545 --> 00:45:16,814
But there's laws
against murder.

946
00:45:16,914 --> 00:45:18,115
Yes, there are, Mr. Moore.

947
00:45:18,215 --> 00:45:19,216
Well, he murdered
our daughter.

948
00:45:19,316 --> 00:45:20,317
Now he's trying to run away.

949
00:45:20,417 --> 00:45:21,952
Don't you understand that?

950
00:45:22,052 --> 00:45:24,555
You think so anyway.

951
00:45:24,655 --> 00:45:27,191
What about all the
insurance policies?

952
00:45:27,291 --> 00:45:28,625
I've already
checked into that.

953
00:45:28,726 --> 00:45:31,128
He stands to get over $300,000.

954
00:45:31,228 --> 00:45:33,097
Yes, and he lied about them.

955
00:45:33,197 --> 00:45:36,100
Which makes the man
guilty of lying, Mrs. Moore.

956
00:45:36,200 --> 00:45:38,202
It doesn't make him
guilty of homicide.

957
00:45:38,302 --> 00:45:40,671
Tell me, Detective, what
the hell does it take?

958
00:45:43,340 --> 00:45:44,742
Well, first you have
to prove that a murder

959
00:45:44,842 --> 00:45:47,511
was even committed.

960
00:45:47,611 --> 00:45:49,780
Your daughter's death
was ruled an accident.

961
00:45:49,880 --> 00:45:51,915
But they'd know that
that wasn't the truth

962
00:45:52,015 --> 00:45:54,184
if they did an autopsy.

963
00:45:54,284 --> 00:45:57,721
Maybe, but they didn't.

964
00:45:57,821 --> 00:46:00,791
Detective, I want you
to understand something.

965
00:46:00,891 --> 00:46:02,059
A mother knows.

966
00:46:02,159 --> 00:46:04,995
[phone ringing]

967
00:46:06,430 --> 00:46:10,834
Well, I don't think you're
going to want to do this,

968
00:46:10,934 --> 00:46:12,236
but there is one
way to settle it.

969
00:46:17,474 --> 00:46:21,812
Shannon Davis, that was
her name for eight months.

970
00:46:21,912 --> 00:46:24,047
She was Shannon
Moore for 24 years.

971
00:46:33,056 --> 00:46:34,958
My name is Donald
Voorhees, Prosecutor

972
00:46:35,058 --> 00:46:37,027
for Hillsboro County.

973
00:46:37,127 --> 00:46:39,263
I have reviewed the report
of the autopsy performed

974
00:46:39,363 --> 00:46:41,765
on the body of Shannon Davis.

975
00:46:41,865 --> 00:46:44,868
I can summarize by saying there
was a single wound at the back

976
00:46:44,968 --> 00:46:47,371
of Mrs. Davis's head
and evidence of bleeding

977
00:46:47,471 --> 00:46:50,340
on the right side of the
brain and that there was

978
00:46:50,440 --> 00:46:52,609
no evidence that Mrs.
Davis had been beaten

979
00:46:52,709 --> 00:46:54,778
or of any foul play.

980
00:46:54,878 --> 00:46:56,547
In short, the injuries
were consistent

981
00:46:56,647 --> 00:46:58,615
with the initial
information, that she

982
00:46:58,715 --> 00:47:00,751
was thrown from her
horse and that she

983
00:47:00,851 --> 00:47:02,686
struck her head on a rock.

984
00:47:02,786 --> 00:47:04,621
I am recommending
that the investigation

985
00:47:04,721 --> 00:47:06,623
by the Hillsboro County
Sheriff's Department

986
00:47:06,723 --> 00:47:09,193
be discontinued.

987
00:47:09,293 --> 00:47:11,228
Well, as far as I'm concerned,
that's good enough for me.

988
00:47:11,328 --> 00:47:13,063
The case is closed.

989
00:47:13,163 --> 00:47:14,898
Isn't it true that
Dave Davis stands

990
00:47:14,998 --> 00:47:18,335
to collect $330,000 in
insurance if his wife's

991
00:47:18,435 --> 00:47:19,436
death is ruled an accident?

992
00:47:23,173 --> 00:47:24,708
I don't think I know you.

993
00:47:24,808 --> 00:47:27,110
Billy Bowles,
Detroit Free Press.

994
00:47:27,211 --> 00:47:30,047
Mr. Bowles, what
you refer to is

995
00:47:30,147 --> 00:47:32,616
circumstantial evidence only.

996
00:47:32,716 --> 00:47:35,652
As I've already explained,
the autopsy report

997
00:47:35,752 --> 00:47:39,056
states that a crime
has not been committed.

998
00:47:39,156 --> 00:47:43,093
Now, if there has been no
crime, I don't really have

999
00:47:43,193 --> 00:47:45,429
to look for suspects now, do I?

1000
00:47:45,529 --> 00:47:48,398
Have you ever even
questioned Mr. Davis?

1001
00:47:48,498 --> 00:47:49,800
You people in the
media want to trial

1002
00:47:49,900 --> 00:47:51,835
a case which doesn't exist.

1003
00:47:51,935 --> 00:47:55,305
Now, you may not have
thought about this,

1004
00:47:55,405 --> 00:47:57,875
but I believe Mr. Davis has
certain rights this department

1005
00:47:57,975 --> 00:47:59,076
has an obligation to protect.

1006
00:47:59,176 --> 00:48:00,544
What about Shannon?

1007
00:48:00,644 --> 00:48:02,112
What about her rights?

1008
00:48:02,212 --> 00:48:03,981
Mrs. Moore, I know
how you must feel.

1009
00:48:04,081 --> 00:48:04,915
Oh, no, you don't.

1010
00:48:05,015 --> 00:48:06,483
Nobody knows how we feel.

1011
00:48:06,583 --> 00:48:09,086
Look, Mr. Voorhees,
we read this report too.

1012
00:48:09,186 --> 00:48:10,220
Let me tell you something.

1013
00:48:10,320 --> 00:48:12,222
I may be a shop steward
for a bunch of painters.

1014
00:48:12,322 --> 00:48:14,725
But the way I read it
is that the coroner

1015
00:48:14,825 --> 00:48:17,394
can't make a proper
autopsy because Shannon

1016
00:48:17,494 --> 00:48:18,695
was already embalmed.

1017
00:48:18,795 --> 00:48:21,899
And when that happens, you
can't test for suffocation.

1018
00:48:21,999 --> 00:48:24,835
Now what do you have
to say about that?

1019
00:48:24,935 --> 00:48:27,137
Well, it's possible that
some mistakes were made.

1020
00:48:27,237 --> 00:48:28,939
But we can only go on
what the experts tell us.

1021
00:48:29,039 --> 00:48:30,073
What experts?

1022
00:48:30,173 --> 00:48:32,643
Mrs. Moore, as I'm
trying to explain,

1023
00:48:32,743 --> 00:48:35,679
every citizen has rights,
including Mr. Davis.

1024
00:48:35,779 --> 00:48:37,814
You're standing up for him.

1025
00:48:37,915 --> 00:48:39,049
What about Shannon?

1026
00:48:39,149 --> 00:48:40,984
She was only 25 years old.

1027
00:48:41,084 --> 00:48:42,719
And she's lying in the ground.

1028
00:48:42,819 --> 00:48:45,122
Who's going to stand
up for Shannon?

1029
00:48:45,222 --> 00:48:47,991
[reporters shouting]

1030
00:48:48,091 --> 00:48:50,661
[music playing]

1031
00:49:01,872 --> 00:49:03,540
Cille, why don't
you come back to bed?

1032
00:49:06,176 --> 00:49:06,977
I can't sleep.

1033
00:49:07,077 --> 00:49:10,314
[music playing]

1034
00:49:14,751 --> 00:49:18,989
Honey, we're doing
everything we possibly can.

1035
00:49:19,089 --> 00:49:20,524
But we can't let
this whole thing

1036
00:49:20,624 --> 00:49:22,993
poison our lives like this.

1037
00:49:23,093 --> 00:49:23,994
Where will it end?

1038
00:49:26,530 --> 00:49:28,832
It'll end when that
killer is behind bars.

1039
00:49:28,932 --> 00:49:31,802
[music playing]

1040
00:49:50,420 --> 00:49:52,189
Are you Alana Henderson?

1041
00:49:52,289 --> 00:49:53,490
Who are you?

1042
00:49:53,590 --> 00:49:55,959
Billy Bowles with
the Detroit Free Press.

1043
00:49:56,059 --> 00:49:57,494
I'm wondering if I
might talk to you

1044
00:49:57,594 --> 00:50:00,330
for a minute about your
ex-husband, Dave Davis.

1045
00:50:00,430 --> 00:50:02,265
I don't have anything
to say about him.

1046
00:50:02,366 --> 00:50:04,768
Please go away.

1047
00:50:04,868 --> 00:50:06,236
You're an important
part of this story.

1048
00:50:06,336 --> 00:50:07,371
No, I'm not.

1049
00:50:07,471 --> 00:50:09,840
Leave my name out of it, please.

1050
00:50:09,940 --> 00:50:11,208
Mrs. Henderson.

1051
00:50:11,308 --> 00:50:14,111
Look, Mr. Bowles, I've got a
restraining order against Dave.

1052
00:50:14,211 --> 00:50:16,880
If I have to, I can
get one against you.

1053
00:50:16,980 --> 00:50:18,749
You won't need that.

1054
00:50:18,849 --> 00:50:22,352
I mean, I'll leave
right now if you want.

1055
00:50:22,452 --> 00:50:24,688
But my editors are going to make
me write this article anyway.

1056
00:50:28,125 --> 00:50:30,527
I feel terrible about
that girl and her family.

1057
00:50:30,627 --> 00:50:31,428
I can tell you that.

1058
00:50:31,528 --> 00:50:32,796
Is that enough?

1059
00:50:32,896 --> 00:50:36,266
Did you ever have reason to
believe that Dave was violent?

1060
00:50:36,366 --> 00:50:38,068
You mean, other than
when he was hitting me?

1061
00:50:41,271 --> 00:50:42,205
I'll try not to take long.

1062
00:50:54,151 --> 00:50:57,621
You said he hit you?

1063
00:50:57,721 --> 00:50:59,523
I was raised Catholic.

1064
00:50:59,623 --> 00:51:00,891
I was determined to
stay in the marriage,

1065
00:51:00,991 --> 00:51:03,560
no matter how bad it got.

1066
00:51:03,660 --> 00:51:08,865
One day, Dave came up behind
me and hit me blindside.

1067
00:51:08,965 --> 00:51:14,104
When I came to, he said you're
lucky you're still alive.

1068
00:51:14,204 --> 00:51:15,372
That's when I filed for divorce.

1069
00:51:27,384 --> 00:51:28,351
Miss Hobson?

1070
00:51:28,452 --> 00:51:29,686
Look, if you're the
man from the paper,

1071
00:51:29,786 --> 00:51:31,021
I don't have anything
to say to you.

1072
00:51:31,121 --> 00:51:33,023
I just need to
ask a few questions.

1073
00:51:33,123 --> 00:51:34,491
Following the death of
Shannon Moore Davis,

1074
00:51:34,591 --> 00:51:36,193
did you go to Florida
with David Davis?

1075
00:51:36,293 --> 00:51:37,260
You don't know the real story.

1076
00:51:37,360 --> 00:51:38,395
Why don't you report that?

1077
00:51:38,495 --> 00:51:39,863
Is David Davis in town now?

1078
00:51:39,963 --> 00:51:41,631
I have nothing to say to you.

1079
00:51:41,731 --> 00:51:42,699
Is that his van?

1080
00:51:42,799 --> 00:51:44,101
Look, she doesn't
have anything to say.

1081
00:51:44,201 --> 00:51:45,302
Didn't you hear?

1082
00:51:45,402 --> 00:51:46,970
Do you have anything
to say, Mr. Davis?

1083
00:51:47,070 --> 00:51:48,405
If I have a statement,
I'll call you.

1084
00:51:48,505 --> 00:51:49,639
Did you kill your wife?

1085
00:51:49,739 --> 00:51:51,341
Why don't you call my
lawyer and get your foot out

1086
00:51:51,441 --> 00:51:52,509
of my door, or
I'll do it for you.

1087
00:51:52,609 --> 00:51:54,077
I thought this was
Miss Hobson's house.

1088
00:52:02,152 --> 00:52:04,321
Davis had been invited
to speak to high school

1089
00:52:04,421 --> 00:52:06,957
students about the Vietnam War.

1090
00:52:07,057 --> 00:52:09,826
He described what it's like
to watch men die in combat.

1091
00:52:09,926 --> 00:52:13,263
And he broke down and cried.

1092
00:52:13,363 --> 00:52:14,731
According to the
Defense Department,

1093
00:52:14,831 --> 00:52:18,602
Dave Davis was never in the
service and never in Vietnam.

1094
00:52:18,702 --> 00:52:21,505
Several of Davis's friends
now say they felt sorry

1095
00:52:21,605 --> 00:52:24,174
for him because of
his many tragedies,

1096
00:52:24,274 --> 00:52:26,076
orphaned as an infant,
wounded in war,

1097
00:52:26,176 --> 00:52:29,179
and blind in a
hospital for a year,

1098
00:52:29,279 --> 00:52:32,482
then injured in an
industrial accident.

1099
00:52:32,582 --> 00:52:34,084
They had learned
that the stories

1100
00:52:34,184 --> 00:52:35,919
Davis told them were untrue.

1101
00:52:36,019 --> 00:52:37,754
For Gods sake,
Dave, don't you have

1102
00:52:37,854 --> 00:52:40,090
something to say about this?

1103
00:52:40,190 --> 00:52:42,959
Everything that I told
you about Vietnam is true.

1104
00:52:43,059 --> 00:52:45,495
But if you ask the
government, they'll deny it.

1105
00:52:45,595 --> 00:52:46,997
I can't tell you
any more about it.

1106
00:52:47,097 --> 00:52:47,998
But I was in the Marines.

1107
00:52:48,098 --> 00:52:49,599
Don't lie to me, Dave.

1108
00:52:49,699 --> 00:52:51,401
You lied to me enough already.

1109
00:52:51,501 --> 00:52:52,769
I've never lied to you.

1110
00:52:52,869 --> 00:52:55,272
You can ask me about anything.

1111
00:52:55,372 --> 00:52:58,008
The insurance
policies, I heard you

1112
00:52:58,108 --> 00:52:59,309
say that you didn't have any.

1113
00:52:59,409 --> 00:53:01,511
And now it turns out
you have six of them.

1114
00:53:01,611 --> 00:53:04,147
I thought they were talking
about health insurance.

1115
00:53:04,247 --> 00:53:07,184
And about the life insurance,
I didn't even know I had any.

1116
00:53:07,284 --> 00:53:11,121
I was confused about what
double indemnity meant.

1117
00:53:11,221 --> 00:53:13,089
I was in shock.

1118
00:53:13,190 --> 00:53:14,124
What about your father?

1119
00:53:14,224 --> 00:53:15,659
You said he died in
World War two II.

1120
00:53:15,759 --> 00:53:18,261
And it says right here,
he lives in Michigan.

1121
00:53:18,361 --> 00:53:19,663
They're right.

1122
00:53:19,763 --> 00:53:23,767
The man listed on those papers
as my father lives in Michigan.

1123
00:53:23,867 --> 00:53:26,203
But that's not my
biological father.

1124
00:53:26,303 --> 00:53:29,906
The man I think of as my father
got my mother pregnant on leave

1125
00:53:30,006 --> 00:53:31,174
but never came home.

1126
00:53:31,274 --> 00:53:32,242
I'm sorry, Dave.

1127
00:53:32,342 --> 00:53:34,010
I'm just not buying
what you're selling.

1128
00:53:34,110 --> 00:53:34,978
Don't be so sure.

1129
00:53:35,078 --> 00:53:35,979
What do you mean?

1130
00:53:38,548 --> 00:53:41,418
Well, I can't live
here anymore, Dick,

1131
00:53:41,518 --> 00:53:42,752
not with all this suspicion.

1132
00:53:42,852 --> 00:53:44,988
Hell, you're my best friend,
but Shannon's parents

1133
00:53:45,088 --> 00:53:47,057
and that reporter have
done such a number on me,

1134
00:53:47,157 --> 00:53:48,391
you don't even believe me.

1135
00:53:48,491 --> 00:53:49,359
I got work to do.

1136
00:53:49,459 --> 00:53:50,360
Dick?

1137
00:53:53,396 --> 00:53:55,565
I was thinking of
selling my farm.

1138
00:53:55,665 --> 00:53:58,535
I thought maybe
you'd like to buy it.

1139
00:53:58,635 --> 00:53:59,769
I'll make you a good deal.

1140
00:54:05,942 --> 00:54:08,178
Well, I was a little
skeptical when I read the letter

1141
00:54:08,278 --> 00:54:10,280
Dick Britton wrote our office.

1142
00:54:10,380 --> 00:54:14,184
My first reaction was,
the girl's parents must

1143
00:54:14,284 --> 00:54:16,519
have stirred up the locals.

1144
00:54:16,620 --> 00:54:18,321
Another case of
grieving parents who

1145
00:54:18,421 --> 00:54:20,357
couldn't accept their
daughter died in an accident.

1146
00:54:20,457 --> 00:54:23,727
This happened sometimes
with grieving parents.

1147
00:54:23,827 --> 00:54:25,762
But then I met them.

1148
00:54:25,862 --> 00:54:27,897
When they bought
the video camera,

1149
00:54:27,998 --> 00:54:29,432
I thought it was a
big waste of money.

1150
00:54:33,737 --> 00:54:36,006
But now when I see
Shannon and Dave, I--

1151
00:54:38,742 --> 00:54:41,978
Maybe it'll help me understand
why you're so suspicious.

1152
00:54:46,449 --> 00:54:48,285
Do you have any idea
how hot it can get driving

1153
00:54:48,385 --> 00:54:50,687
home to Hillsboro from Toledo in
a car without air-conditioning?

1154
00:54:50,787 --> 00:54:53,023
Well, I don't know,
but it's pretty sweaty.

1155
00:54:53,123 --> 00:54:55,458
Anyway, we still don't
have air-conditioning,

1156
00:54:55,558 --> 00:54:57,827
but it's not a problem anymore.

1157
00:54:57,927 --> 00:54:59,863
Look at this.

1158
00:54:59,963 --> 00:55:02,699
[giggles]

1159
00:55:02,799 --> 00:55:03,600
Hi, Tom.

1160
00:55:03,700 --> 00:55:05,001
Hi, Cille.

1161
00:55:05,101 --> 00:55:07,203
How do you like the car?

1162
00:55:07,304 --> 00:55:10,040
He borrowed $10,000
to buy that car.

1163
00:55:10,140 --> 00:55:12,676
And then he takes out more
life insurance on Shannon,

1164
00:55:12,776 --> 00:55:18,014
so that if she dies,
the loan gets paid off.

1165
00:55:18,114 --> 00:55:19,749
He now owns that
car free and clear.

1166
00:55:24,754 --> 00:55:25,855
Honey, bring the camera over.

1167
00:55:25,955 --> 00:55:27,157
I want to say hi to
your mom and dad.

1168
00:55:27,257 --> 00:55:28,925
Erica!

1169
00:55:29,025 --> 00:55:29,926
Oh.

1170
00:55:34,898 --> 00:55:35,732
No, I'm sorry.

1171
00:55:35,832 --> 00:55:37,334
I just can't stand
to watch this.

1172
00:55:40,070 --> 00:55:42,572
What I don't understand
is why would her shoes be

1173
00:55:42,672 --> 00:55:44,774
off if she fell from the horse?

1174
00:55:44,874 --> 00:55:47,644
Why would the laces be untied?

1175
00:55:47,744 --> 00:55:50,680
Something happened in those
woods that was not an accident.

1176
00:55:53,783 --> 00:55:57,053
Detective Brooks,
can you help us?

1177
00:55:57,153 --> 00:55:58,421
We're running out
of people to ask.

1178
00:56:01,091 --> 00:56:01,991
I don't know.

1179
00:56:07,497 --> 00:56:09,332
But I'm going to try.

1180
00:56:09,432 --> 00:56:10,233
Thank you.

1181
00:56:10,333 --> 00:56:13,837
[music playing]

1182
00:56:36,326 --> 00:56:37,861
Are you Dr. Roger Fulbright?

1183
00:56:37,961 --> 00:56:39,929
That's me.

1184
00:56:40,029 --> 00:56:41,498
That must make you
the eager, young

1185
00:56:41,598 --> 00:56:45,568
detective with the grand
theory about the Davis case.

1186
00:56:45,668 --> 00:56:47,170
I've got a theory, yes.

1187
00:56:47,270 --> 00:56:49,539
Well, I'm chained to the
desk for the afternoon,

1188
00:56:49,639 --> 00:56:51,775
so let's hear it.

1189
00:56:51,875 --> 00:56:52,776
All right.

1190
00:56:55,311 --> 00:56:57,080
Davis and his wife were
alone in the woods.

1191
00:56:57,180 --> 00:56:59,382
But he knew he couldn't
repeatedly strike her head

1192
00:56:59,482 --> 00:57:00,950
again and again if he
wanted us to believe

1193
00:57:01,050 --> 00:57:02,419
she died falling off a horse.

1194
00:57:02,519 --> 00:57:05,054
Meaning, you think he only
had one chance to connect

1195
00:57:05,155 --> 00:57:06,790
her head with that rock.

1196
00:57:06,890 --> 00:57:07,991
He had to be sure
she wasn't going

1197
00:57:08,091 --> 00:57:09,259
to put up much of a fight.

1198
00:57:09,359 --> 00:57:11,628
Therefore, our young
detective theorizes

1199
00:57:11,728 --> 00:57:14,898
Davis might have used some
kind of drug to immobilize her.

1200
00:57:14,998 --> 00:57:16,232
He took pharmacology classes.

1201
00:57:16,332 --> 00:57:17,400
He's a smart guy.

1202
00:57:17,500 --> 00:57:19,302
Wouldn't a smart
guy worry that might

1203
00:57:19,402 --> 00:57:20,470
turn up in our lab work?

1204
00:57:20,570 --> 00:57:21,871
Not if he thought he
could sell the horse story

1205
00:57:21,971 --> 00:57:23,306
and get her cremated right away.

1206
00:57:31,481 --> 00:57:35,351
Chemical analysis of
Shannon Moore's tissue.

1207
00:57:35,452 --> 00:57:36,252
What's this?

1208
00:57:36,352 --> 00:57:38,321
Could be your drug.

1209
00:57:38,421 --> 00:57:39,856
You knew about this all along?

1210
00:57:39,956 --> 00:57:41,991
It also be a fatty acid.

1211
00:57:42,091 --> 00:57:45,829
So far, we've eliminated
about 1,000 possibilities out

1212
00:57:45,929 --> 00:57:47,263
of, oh, say, a quarter million.

1213
00:57:47,363 --> 00:57:48,331
So keep checking.

1214
00:57:48,431 --> 00:57:49,699
It doesn't work that way.

1215
00:57:49,799 --> 00:57:51,968
I don't have the time, the
money, or the equipment

1216
00:57:52,068 --> 00:57:53,636
to track this down.

1217
00:57:53,736 --> 00:57:55,972
I'm never going to be able
to tell you what it is.

1218
00:57:56,072 --> 00:57:57,440
You have to tell me.

1219
00:57:57,540 --> 00:57:59,809
And then I try to verify it.

1220
00:57:59,909 --> 00:58:02,312
I have to tell you?

1221
00:58:02,412 --> 00:58:06,382
Isn't that why they pay
you the big bucks, Detective?

1222
00:58:06,483 --> 00:58:09,986
[music playing]

1223
00:58:15,992 --> 00:58:20,630
Look at him, just look
at him, that son of a--

1224
00:58:20,730 --> 00:58:24,801
I want you to go in there,
sit across the table from him,

1225
00:58:24,901 --> 00:58:26,236
show him you're
not afraid of him.

1226
00:58:26,336 --> 00:58:28,938
Yeah, well, I'm afraid
of what I might do to him.

1227
00:58:29,038 --> 00:58:30,273
He should be on
trial for murder.

1228
00:58:30,373 --> 00:58:32,275
Why should I have to sue
him for wrongful death?

1229
00:58:32,375 --> 00:58:34,477
If we win this suit, we
keep the insurance money

1230
00:58:34,577 --> 00:58:35,945
out of Dave's hands.

1231
00:58:36,045 --> 00:58:38,014
The minute he gets
it, he could run.

1232
00:58:38,114 --> 00:58:42,685
Whatever we have to do
to get him, for Shannon.

1233
00:58:42,785 --> 00:58:47,323
[sighs]

1234
00:58:47,423 --> 00:58:49,325
All right now, let me
just try to summarize

1235
00:58:49,425 --> 00:58:51,494
some of these things.

1236
00:58:51,594 --> 00:58:54,931
Death of your father, playing
football for Bo Shembechler

1237
00:58:55,031 --> 00:58:58,401
in the Rose Bowl,
serving in Vietnam,

1238
00:58:58,501 --> 00:59:00,303
growing up in an orphanage.

1239
00:59:00,403 --> 00:59:04,307
Now you've admitted lying about
all these things, haven't you?

1240
00:59:04,407 --> 00:59:05,742
Apparently so.

1241
00:59:05,842 --> 00:59:06,643
Let me ask you something.

1242
00:59:06,743 --> 00:59:08,177
Help me out here.

1243
00:59:08,278 --> 00:59:13,283
Why tell people something
if it's not true?

1244
00:59:13,383 --> 00:59:15,251
I have no answer.

1245
00:59:15,351 --> 00:59:17,854
Your answer is
you have no answer.

1246
00:59:17,954 --> 00:59:18,855
That's what he said.

1247
00:59:22,058 --> 00:59:23,993
Let's get back to Shannon.

1248
00:59:24,093 --> 00:59:24,928
Did you love her?

1249
00:59:25,028 --> 00:59:26,229
Of course.

1250
00:59:26,329 --> 00:59:27,697
Of course.

1251
00:59:27,797 --> 00:59:29,899
Now, you've told us, you
traveled to Florida two days

1252
00:59:29,999 --> 00:59:31,301
after your wife's funeral.

1253
00:59:31,401 --> 00:59:34,470
Who did you go with?

1254
00:59:34,571 --> 00:59:37,407
A-- a friend helped
me to drive there.

1255
00:59:37,507 --> 00:59:38,775
What was the name
of that friend?

1256
00:59:42,145 --> 00:59:43,313
Jerri Hobson.

1257
00:59:43,413 --> 00:59:45,081
Jerri Hobson.

1258
00:59:45,181 --> 00:59:47,884
That's a woman's name
though, isn't it?

1259
00:59:47,984 --> 00:59:48,851
Yes.

1260
00:59:48,952 --> 00:59:50,186
The time it took
traveling to Florida

1261
00:59:50,286 --> 00:59:53,990
involved overnight
stops, did it not?

1262
00:59:54,090 --> 00:59:54,958
Yes.

1263
00:59:55,058 --> 00:59:56,926
Yes.

1264
00:59:57,026 --> 01:00:00,029
Did you and Jerri Hobson
share a room during that trip?

1265
01:00:00,129 --> 01:00:01,431
I don't have to
answer that question.

1266
01:00:01,531 --> 01:00:03,666
Oh, Mr. Davis,
I'm afraid you do.

1267
01:00:03,766 --> 01:00:07,971
You're sworn as if you were
standing in front of a judge.

1268
01:00:08,071 --> 01:00:08,972
Do you want to tell him?

1269
01:00:12,475 --> 01:00:15,845
You need to answer it.

1270
01:00:15,945 --> 01:00:17,714
The question is, did
you and Jerri Hobson

1271
01:00:17,814 --> 01:00:19,716
share a room during
a trip to Florida

1272
01:00:19,816 --> 01:00:21,517
immediately after
your wife's funeral?

1273
01:00:28,925 --> 01:00:30,126
Yes.

1274
01:00:30,226 --> 01:00:31,494
Son of a bitch.

1275
01:00:31,594 --> 01:00:33,396
You never loved
anybody but yourself.

1276
01:00:33,496 --> 01:00:35,064
Please, Mr. Moore,
any more outbursts,

1277
01:00:35,164 --> 01:00:37,567
you'll have to leave the room.

1278
01:00:37,667 --> 01:00:38,968
Let's continue, Mr. Davis.

1279
01:00:39,068 --> 01:00:41,270
Let's go back to the
day of the accident.

1280
01:00:41,371 --> 01:00:43,806
Did you pull your
wife from her horse

1281
01:00:43,906 --> 01:00:45,675
and hit her head against a rock?

1282
01:00:45,775 --> 01:00:47,010
No.

1283
01:00:47,110 --> 01:00:48,878
Why should we believe you
now, when you've acknowledged

1284
01:00:48,978 --> 01:00:50,913
that you've lied in the past?

1285
01:00:51,014 --> 01:00:52,281
I didn't kill my wife.

1286
01:00:52,382 --> 01:00:54,817
That's why you should believe
me, because I didn't do it.

1287
01:00:54,917 --> 01:00:57,253
[intense music]

1288
01:00:57,353 --> 01:00:59,355
I didn't do it.

1289
01:01:06,162 --> 01:01:09,532
[cheerful music]

1290
01:01:09,632 --> 01:01:12,568
[chatter]

1291
01:01:21,611 --> 01:01:22,612
- You're kidding?
- No

1292
01:01:22,712 --> 01:01:23,579
You have a satellite phone?

1293
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:26,349
Yes, I do.

1294
01:01:26,449 --> 01:01:28,618
And that's the guy I'm
going to interview.

1295
01:01:28,718 --> 01:01:30,286
For your bodyguard company?

1296
01:01:30,386 --> 01:01:33,056
Mm-hmm.

1297
01:01:33,156 --> 01:01:34,257
He doesn't look that tough.

1298
01:01:34,357 --> 01:01:36,159
Well, looks can be deceiving.

1299
01:01:36,259 --> 01:01:37,960
I'll just be a few seconds.

1300
01:01:38,061 --> 01:01:41,497
[cheerful music]

1301
01:01:46,869 --> 01:01:48,171
Congratulations.

1302
01:01:48,271 --> 01:01:51,240
You're now fully licensed to
drive in the Sunshine State.

1303
01:01:51,340 --> 01:01:52,141
Oh, this is good.

1304
01:01:52,241 --> 01:01:53,609
Nothing but the best.

1305
01:01:53,710 --> 01:01:55,845
I also paid for
Social Security.

1306
01:01:59,849 --> 01:02:00,583
What's this?

1307
01:02:00,683 --> 01:02:01,851
It's a library card.

1308
01:02:01,951 --> 01:02:05,188
It's a blue-light bonus special,
just a little insurance.

1309
01:02:05,288 --> 01:02:06,923
Oh, you can never
have too much insurance.

1310
01:02:07,023 --> 01:02:10,393
[cheerful music]

1311
01:02:21,037 --> 01:02:23,206
Detective Brooks,
Michigan State Police.

1312
01:02:23,306 --> 01:02:25,875
Do I have to talk to you?

1313
01:02:25,975 --> 01:02:27,443
Not yet.

1314
01:02:27,543 --> 01:02:28,745
Where's Dave?

1315
01:02:28,845 --> 01:02:29,645
Florida.

1316
01:02:29,746 --> 01:02:32,348
That's where he lives now.

1317
01:02:32,448 --> 01:02:34,450
Maybe he told you
about his deposition?

1318
01:02:34,550 --> 01:02:36,519
That's nothing to do with me.

1319
01:02:36,619 --> 01:02:38,321
I think it does.

1320
01:02:38,421 --> 01:02:39,589
You stayed at a motel
with a man whose

1321
01:02:39,689 --> 01:02:41,557
wife died three days before.

1322
01:02:41,657 --> 01:02:43,760
I'd say that's pretty suspicious
behavior from both of you.

1323
01:02:43,860 --> 01:02:45,695
I had nothing to do
with that woman's death.

1324
01:02:45,795 --> 01:02:46,662
I believe you.

1325
01:02:46,763 --> 01:02:47,964
But you got to admit
it, it sounds--

1326
01:02:48,064 --> 01:02:50,733
Dave told me my
name never came up.

1327
01:02:50,833 --> 01:02:54,804
Wouldn't be the first time
he lied to you, would it?

1328
01:02:54,904 --> 01:02:56,906
Do you know for a
fact that this Shannon

1329
01:02:57,006 --> 01:03:00,643
Moore wasn't in the
Witness Protection Program?

1330
01:03:00,743 --> 01:03:03,146
Is that what he told you?

1331
01:03:03,246 --> 01:03:04,914
Shannon Moore is no witness.

1332
01:03:05,014 --> 01:03:08,084
She's the victim.

1333
01:03:08,184 --> 01:03:10,653
Well, are you sure
it's really her?

1334
01:03:10,753 --> 01:03:12,088
That it's really her body?

1335
01:03:12,188 --> 01:03:13,156
It's her.

1336
01:03:13,256 --> 01:03:16,659
Whatever he told you, it's her.

1337
01:03:16,759 --> 01:03:18,294
They were really married.

1338
01:03:18,394 --> 01:03:19,295
And she's dead.

1339
01:03:22,665 --> 01:03:25,001
But Dave works for the
government, doesn't he?

1340
01:03:25,101 --> 01:03:28,037
I mean, he's an
agent or something?

1341
01:03:28,137 --> 01:03:29,272
It's one of his
better stories.

1342
01:03:36,012 --> 01:03:37,313
God, I've been so stupid.

1343
01:03:39,916 --> 01:03:43,786
If I had married
him, I'd be the--

1344
01:03:43,886 --> 01:03:45,488
He talked about marriage?

1345
01:03:45,588 --> 01:03:48,090
Almost from the beginning.

1346
01:03:48,191 --> 01:03:50,493
Why didn't you marry him?

1347
01:03:50,593 --> 01:03:51,494
I wasn't ready.

1348
01:03:54,597 --> 01:03:56,032
I mean, he scared me off.

1349
01:03:56,132 --> 01:04:00,102
He still had the rings from the
woman before me who backed out.

1350
01:04:00,203 --> 01:04:01,237
It was all too planned.

1351
01:04:04,207 --> 01:04:07,577
This woman before you,
you remember her name?

1352
01:04:07,677 --> 01:04:08,578
Yeah.

1353
01:04:11,747 --> 01:04:13,449
He's in trouble, huh?

1354
01:04:13,549 --> 01:04:14,350
He's under investigation.

1355
01:04:14,450 --> 01:04:17,153
What's his is background?

1356
01:04:17,253 --> 01:04:18,621
I don't know what
I can tell you.

1357
01:04:18,721 --> 01:04:21,290
It's been a few years.

1358
01:04:21,390 --> 01:04:23,593
Dave came and went
a lot from my life.

1359
01:04:23,693 --> 01:04:27,296
He's always Tokyo, or
Belize, or something.

1360
01:04:27,396 --> 01:04:29,232
You know, he works for the CIA.

1361
01:04:29,332 --> 01:04:30,600
Mm-hmm.

1362
01:04:30,700 --> 01:04:32,335
I guess, "worked" is
probably the word now

1363
01:04:32,435 --> 01:04:33,336
that he's in this trouble.

1364
01:04:36,172 --> 01:04:37,640
Did he ever propose?

1365
01:04:37,740 --> 01:04:39,609
Cappy?

1366
01:04:39,709 --> 01:04:41,043
Oh, yeah.

1367
01:04:41,143 --> 01:04:42,245
Cappy?

1368
01:04:42,345 --> 01:04:46,282
He gave himself a
nickname, Cappy, for Captain.

1369
01:04:46,382 --> 01:04:49,018
He thought he was
a big time sailor.

1370
01:04:49,118 --> 01:04:50,786
But you didn't marry him?

1371
01:04:50,887 --> 01:04:52,788
Almost did.

1372
01:04:52,889 --> 01:04:53,923
We had the tickets.

1373
01:04:54,023 --> 01:04:56,826
And I was almost on the
plane when I backed out.

1374
01:04:56,926 --> 01:04:58,494
Where were you
going to get married?

1375
01:04:58,594 --> 01:05:00,496
Las Vegas.

1376
01:05:00,596 --> 01:05:04,400
He wanted to get married in one
of those tacky, little chapels.

1377
01:05:04,500 --> 01:05:07,837
I just-- I just
couldn't handle that.

1378
01:05:07,937 --> 01:05:10,773
Ever remember Dave talking
about drugs, bring up subject?

1379
01:05:14,443 --> 01:05:16,913
I know this is what
you're looking for,

1380
01:05:17,013 --> 01:05:20,549
but I remember one time,
this must have been 1978.

1381
01:05:20,650 --> 01:05:22,551
He read me an article
about some physician

1382
01:05:22,652 --> 01:05:25,354
that F. Lee Bailey defended,
used a drug he said

1383
01:05:25,454 --> 01:05:27,123
was the perfect murder
weapon because after it

1384
01:05:27,223 --> 01:05:30,426
kills somebody, it can't
be detected in an autopsy.

1385
01:05:30,526 --> 01:05:31,661
He actually told you that?

1386
01:05:31,761 --> 01:05:32,995
Oh, yeah.

1387
01:05:33,095 --> 01:05:35,965
Dave could get excited about
some pretty unusual things.

1388
01:05:36,065 --> 01:05:37,566
He used to read a lot
of murder mysteries.

1389
01:05:46,242 --> 01:05:47,143
Try this.

1390
01:05:50,446 --> 01:05:55,284
Intact and dioxin chloride,
a pretty good guess for rookie.

1391
01:05:55,384 --> 01:05:56,419
Where'd you get this?

1392
01:05:56,519 --> 01:05:57,987
A lot of farmers like
Davis have access to it.

1393
01:05:58,087 --> 01:05:58,955
See if it matches.

1394
01:05:59,055 --> 01:06:01,324
Oh, it kills people
dead, all right,

1395
01:06:01,424 --> 01:06:02,959
paralyzes every
muscle in the body,

1396
01:06:03,059 --> 01:06:04,727
so you can't even breathe.

1397
01:06:04,827 --> 01:06:06,495
The problem is after
about 10 minutes

1398
01:06:06,595 --> 01:06:07,997
it breaks down in human tissue.

1399
01:06:08,097 --> 01:06:09,865
So guys like me can't find it.

1400
01:06:09,966 --> 01:06:10,766
Sorry.

1401
01:06:10,866 --> 01:06:13,235
Try it anyway.

1402
01:06:13,336 --> 01:06:15,738
Well, if it will make you
feel better, we'll rule it out.

1403
01:06:15,838 --> 01:06:17,506
And then you can
get back to work.

1404
01:06:17,606 --> 01:06:19,809
Great.

1405
01:06:19,909 --> 01:06:22,578
[music playing]

1406
01:06:22,678 --> 01:06:26,916
It'll only take a couple
of minutes to get a reading.

1407
01:06:27,016 --> 01:06:29,785
[music playing]

1408
01:06:45,568 --> 01:06:48,104
You know this is the one
with dioxin chloride, right?

1409
01:06:48,204 --> 01:06:51,607
Now this is the
unknown compound found

1410
01:06:51,707 --> 01:06:55,311
in Shannon Moore's tissues.

1411
01:06:55,411 --> 01:06:56,212
Bingo.

1412
01:06:56,312 --> 01:06:58,214
Perfect match.

1413
01:06:58,314 --> 01:07:00,483
I've got to run more
tests to replicate this.

1414
01:07:00,583 --> 01:07:03,419
I've got to be able to prove you
can extract dioxinol chloride

1415
01:07:03,519 --> 01:07:04,720
from human tissue.

1416
01:07:04,820 --> 01:07:07,323
But if I can, it sure looks
like you've got your man.

1417
01:07:07,423 --> 01:07:09,725
This gives me the proof
Shannon Moore was murdered.

1418
01:07:09,825 --> 01:07:13,662
I still got to prove Dave
Davis had access to the drug.

1419
01:07:13,763 --> 01:07:16,999
Hey, Detective, good call.

1420
01:07:17,099 --> 01:07:19,902
[music playing]

1421
01:07:22,671 --> 01:07:26,709
Detective Brooks,
this is my niece Tracy.

1422
01:07:26,809 --> 01:07:27,610
Hi, Tracy.

1423
01:07:27,710 --> 01:07:29,245
Hi, Detective.

1424
01:07:29,345 --> 01:07:31,247
Honey, you just tell
him what you told us.

1425
01:07:36,018 --> 01:07:39,155
Well, there are about a
dozen needles in the butter

1426
01:07:39,255 --> 01:07:40,623
compartment in the fridge.

1427
01:07:40,723 --> 01:07:41,757
Hypodermic needles?

1428
01:07:41,857 --> 01:07:44,860
Yeah, I guess Dave used
them for the animals.

1429
01:07:44,960 --> 01:07:47,263
There were also some
vials in the freezer.

1430
01:07:47,363 --> 01:07:49,965
You know the kind where
you put the needle

1431
01:07:50,066 --> 01:07:51,567
through and pull the drug out?

1432
01:07:51,667 --> 01:07:53,769
Do you remember
the name of the drug?

1433
01:07:53,869 --> 01:07:55,404
I don't know.

1434
01:07:55,504 --> 01:07:57,406
It sounded like penicillin.

1435
01:07:57,506 --> 01:07:59,708
But I guess I'm just not sure.

1436
01:07:59,809 --> 01:08:01,610
Take a look.

1437
01:08:01,710 --> 01:08:02,645
There are five names here.

1438
01:08:02,745 --> 01:08:04,747
Can you remember one of them?

1439
01:08:04,847 --> 01:08:05,848
They look like anyway.

1440
01:08:11,620 --> 01:08:13,856
That one.

1441
01:08:13,956 --> 01:08:14,857
Which one?

1442
01:08:14,957 --> 01:08:19,628
I don't know how
you say it, Pentactin.

1443
01:08:19,728 --> 01:08:21,664
OK.

1444
01:08:21,764 --> 01:08:24,533
Well, thanks.

1445
01:08:24,633 --> 01:08:26,869
Sorry I couldn't
be of more help.

1446
01:08:26,969 --> 01:08:27,770
Thanks, Tracy.

1447
01:08:27,870 --> 01:08:31,273
[music playing]

1448
01:08:31,373 --> 01:08:32,875
I'm sorry it
wasn't that dioxin

1449
01:08:32,975 --> 01:08:36,112
or whatever it is
you were looking for.

1450
01:08:36,212 --> 01:08:41,083
There are seven brand
names for dioxinol chloride.

1451
01:08:41,183 --> 01:08:44,186
And one of them is Pentactin.

1452
01:08:44,286 --> 01:08:47,123
Oh, my god.

1453
01:08:47,223 --> 01:08:48,424
You've both been
through so much.

1454
01:08:48,524 --> 01:08:51,927
I don't know how
to ask you this.

1455
01:08:52,027 --> 01:08:54,730
We need your permission
to exhume Shannon again.

1456
01:08:54,830 --> 01:08:58,000
[music playing]

1457
01:09:00,936 --> 01:09:01,737
Dave?

1458
01:09:01,837 --> 01:09:02,638
Just checking in.

1459
01:09:02,738 --> 01:09:04,006
Dave, where the hell are you?

1460
01:09:04,106 --> 01:09:05,074
I'm around.

1461
01:09:05,174 --> 01:09:05,975
Hey, listen.

1462
01:09:06,075 --> 01:09:07,276
Where are you?

1463
01:09:07,376 --> 01:09:10,479
Are you getting any closer
to settling that civil suit?

1464
01:09:10,579 --> 01:09:12,481
It's not a civil
matter anymore, Dave.

1465
01:09:12,581 --> 01:09:13,415
What do you mean?

1466
01:09:13,516 --> 01:09:15,417
I mean, since you
last checked in,

1467
01:09:15,518 --> 01:09:19,155
they exhumed Shannon Moore's
body, looking for needle marks.

1468
01:09:19,255 --> 01:09:22,391
They found some,
impaneled a grand jury.

1469
01:09:22,491 --> 01:09:26,095
There's a federal warrant
out for your arrest.

1470
01:09:26,195 --> 01:09:27,363
Are they out of their minds?

1471
01:09:27,463 --> 01:09:31,300
Dave, they may be, but your
position now is critical.

1472
01:09:31,400 --> 01:09:33,002
So as my attorney,
what's your advice?

1473
01:09:33,102 --> 01:09:35,971
My advice is to get your
butt back to Michigan ASAP.

1474
01:09:36,071 --> 01:09:37,006
This is no game, Dave.

1475
01:09:37,106 --> 01:09:38,073
This is a murder charge.

1476
01:09:38,174 --> 01:09:38,974
OK.

1477
01:09:39,074 --> 01:09:40,009
OK.

1478
01:09:40,109 --> 01:09:41,410
I'll take the first plane back.

1479
01:09:41,510 --> 01:09:43,646
Where are you?

1480
01:09:43,746 --> 01:09:44,547
I'm on my way.

1481
01:09:44,647 --> 01:09:45,581
Never mind.

1482
01:09:45,681 --> 01:09:48,918
[music playing]

1483
01:09:49,018 --> 01:09:51,453
What is it?

1484
01:09:51,554 --> 01:09:54,056
I'm being charged with
negligence in the death of my--

1485
01:09:54,156 --> 01:09:55,257
my wife.

1486
01:09:55,357 --> 01:09:56,892
I've got to return to Michigan.

1487
01:09:56,992 --> 01:09:58,260
How soon?

1488
01:09:58,360 --> 01:10:00,930
Well, I've got to get you
on a plane back to Lansing.

1489
01:10:01,030 --> 01:10:02,464
And then I'll--

1490
01:10:02,565 --> 01:10:04,867
I'll follow in a few days.

1491
01:10:04,967 --> 01:10:07,036
Did you hurt your wife, Dave?

1492
01:10:07,136 --> 01:10:10,105
Mona, I hurt my
wife about as much

1493
01:10:10,206 --> 01:10:12,808
as I've hurt you,
which is not at all.

1494
01:10:12,908 --> 01:10:14,310
And I loved her
the way I love you.

1495
01:10:14,410 --> 01:10:17,279
[music playing]

1496
01:10:23,018 --> 01:10:24,520
[background chatter]

1497
01:10:24,620 --> 01:10:25,788
Hi.

1498
01:10:25,888 --> 01:10:27,056
Hi.

1499
01:10:27,156 --> 01:10:28,657
Can I help you?

1500
01:10:28,757 --> 01:10:30,326
I'd like to buy
a ticket to Hawaii.

1501
01:10:30,426 --> 01:10:31,227
OK.

1502
01:10:31,327 --> 01:10:32,595
Your name, please?

1503
01:10:32,695 --> 01:10:34,330
Bell, David Meyer Bell.

1504
01:10:34,430 --> 01:10:37,433
[music playing]

1505
01:11:00,789 --> 01:11:02,124
Don, you look
like a drowned rat.

1506
01:11:02,224 --> 01:11:03,125
Come on in.

1507
01:11:05,461 --> 01:11:06,328
Bob?

1508
01:11:13,869 --> 01:11:15,938
We lost him.

1509
01:11:16,038 --> 01:11:16,839
[sighs]

1510
01:11:16,939 --> 01:11:19,875
[music playing]

1511
01:11:31,086 --> 01:11:32,354
We tried everything.

1512
01:11:32,454 --> 01:11:34,089
We even printed
thousands of flyers,

1513
01:11:34,189 --> 01:11:37,226
distributed them in Florida
and the Caribbean area.

1514
01:11:37,326 --> 01:11:40,296
We followed leads, nothing.

1515
01:11:40,396 --> 01:11:43,899
In 1979, Dave Davis
married Shannon Moore.

1516
01:11:43,999 --> 01:11:46,902
In 1980, he killed her.

1517
01:11:47,002 --> 01:11:49,838
By 1987, it looked
like he'd gotten

1518
01:11:49,938 --> 01:11:52,541
away with the perfect crime.

1519
01:11:52,641 --> 01:11:53,676
I hated that.
[knocking]

1520
01:11:53,776 --> 01:11:54,677
Yeah.

1521
01:11:57,279 --> 01:11:58,280
Hey, Jack.

1522
01:11:58,380 --> 01:11:59,148
Hello.

1523
01:11:59,248 --> 01:12:00,182
How you doing?

1524
01:12:00,282 --> 01:12:02,484
Got an idea on the
Dave Davis case.

1525
01:12:02,584 --> 01:12:05,421
You're still the assigned
prosecutor, right?

1526
01:12:05,521 --> 01:12:07,156
Yeah, it's somewhere in
the bottom of that pile.

1527
01:12:07,256 --> 01:12:09,725
Well, get it out.

1528
01:12:09,825 --> 01:12:13,462
I got a plan to find him.

1529
01:12:13,562 --> 01:12:15,631
Look, Brooks, Davis is dead.

1530
01:12:15,731 --> 01:12:16,765
All right.

1531
01:12:16,865 --> 01:12:19,401
He probably tried to con
some Caribbean bad ass.

1532
01:12:19,501 --> 01:12:20,469
He's too smart for that.

1533
01:12:20,569 --> 01:12:22,304
He's alive.

1534
01:12:22,404 --> 01:12:26,742
So what's this
brilliant new plan?

1535
01:12:26,842 --> 01:12:27,843
Unsolved Mysteries.

1536
01:12:27,943 --> 01:12:28,744
Oh.

1537
01:12:28,844 --> 01:12:29,645
Why not?

1538
01:12:29,745 --> 01:12:30,646
We've done everything else.

1539
01:12:30,746 --> 01:12:32,047
It's the only way
we're going to get

1540
01:12:32,147 --> 01:12:33,515
that case from the bottom of the
stack and put it on top again.

1541
01:12:33,615 --> 01:12:34,817
Well, we can't.

1542
01:12:34,917 --> 01:12:36,151
The grand jury judge said
we can't talk to the media.

1543
01:12:36,251 --> 01:12:38,087
Let's call him up
and ask him again.

1544
01:12:38,187 --> 01:12:41,623
I mean, Jack, we do nothing,
this guy got away with murder.

1545
01:12:41,724 --> 01:12:44,860
You didn't get into this
business to let people do that.

1546
01:12:44,960 --> 01:12:46,762
We tried everything else.

1547
01:12:46,862 --> 01:12:48,163
What do we got to lose?

1548
01:12:48,263 --> 01:12:51,200
[phone ringing]

1549
01:12:53,168 --> 01:12:55,237
Well, I suppose it
wouldn't hurt to ask.

1550
01:12:58,140 --> 01:12:59,808
If Shannon's death
had been an accident,

1551
01:12:59,908 --> 01:13:03,011
I could have accepted it.

1552
01:13:03,112 --> 01:13:05,914
But what I couldn't
accept was seeing

1553
01:13:06,014 --> 01:13:10,552
a young girl ride
off on horseback

1554
01:13:10,652 --> 01:13:11,920
and never come back to me.

1555
01:13:15,958 --> 01:13:18,127
What happened out there?

1556
01:13:18,227 --> 01:13:21,163
I don't know.

1557
01:13:21,263 --> 01:13:23,999
I do know that
she called for me.

1558
01:13:24,099 --> 01:13:26,735
And I didn't hear her.

1559
01:13:26,835 --> 01:13:27,836
I can't accept that.

1560
01:13:27,936 --> 01:13:28,737
I won't.

1561
01:13:28,837 --> 01:13:29,638
That's all right.

1562
01:13:29,738 --> 01:13:30,939
We're-- we're going to get him.

1563
01:13:31,039 --> 01:13:34,543
Wherever he is he, he knows
we're still after him.

1564
01:13:34,643 --> 01:13:35,444
We'll get him.

1565
01:13:35,544 --> 01:13:36,645
We'll get him.

1566
01:13:36,745 --> 01:13:40,115
[intense music]

1567
01:13:44,420 --> 01:13:48,524
On July 23, 1980, a small
Michigan farming community,

1568
01:13:48,624 --> 01:13:51,226
newlyweds Dave and Shannon
Davis prepared to go

1569
01:13:51,326 --> 01:13:54,196
for a sunset horseback ride.

1570
01:13:54,296 --> 01:13:56,999
Within an hour,
Shannon was dead.

1571
01:14:00,302 --> 01:14:02,671
After Shannon's death,
Bob and Lucille Moore

1572
01:14:02,771 --> 01:14:04,606
began to discover
that Dave Davis was

1573
01:14:04,706 --> 01:14:07,376
not the man he seemed to be.

